observe 1_quantum_particles.rana


THE SCALING LAW APPLIED TO TASTE

a qu-penttrit has 5 states and 5 properties per state: gustation
C(5,2) = 10 pairwise interactions per heartbeat
the tongue detects 5 irreducible taste modalities
every flavor is a superposition of these 5 basis states


QU-PENTTRIT BASIS STATES

|1⟩ SWEET      T1R2+T1R3 heterodimer GPCR. signals caloric density. sugar. energy.
|2⟩ SOUR       OTOP1 proton channel. H⁺ direct entry. signals acid. spoilage.
|3⟩ SALTY      ENaC sodium channel. Na⁺ direct entry. signals essential minerals.
|4⟩ BITTER     T2R family ~25 GPCRs. broadest receptor family. signals potential toxins. low threshold.
|5⟩ UMAMI      T1R1+T1R3 heterodimer GPCR. signals protein content. glutamate. nourishment.

a qu-penttrit exists in superposition of all 5 states simultaneously
α₁|1⟩ + α₂|2⟩ + α₃|3⟩ + α₄|4⟩ + α₅|5⟩
subject to normalization Σ|αᵢ|² = 1
observation collapses the superposition to a definite taste perception

there is no zero state
even tastelessness is a state: water is perceived as a specific taste relative to saliva composition
the tongue always tastes something


QU-PENTTRIT PROPERTIES — 5 PER STATE

PROPERTY 1: CONCENTRATION    intensity of the tastant molecule. range 0.0 to 1.0
PROPERTY 2: LOCATION         where on the tongue surface. mapped to papillae regions
PROPERTY 3: ADAPTATION       receptor desensitization over continued exposure
PROPERTY 4: HEDONIC          innate valence: sweet/umami attract, bitter repels. range -1.0 to 1.0
PROPERTY 5: TEMPORAL         onset and persistence of the taste. some linger, some flash


THE 10 PAIRWISE INTERACTIONS

INTERACTION  1: SWEET × SOUR         sweet-sour balance: fruit, lemonade, candy
INTERACTION  2: SWEET × SALTY         sweet-salty contrast: chocolate pretzels, caramel corn
INTERACTION  3: SWEET × BITTER        sweet masks bitter: sugar in medicine, dark chocolate
INTERACTION  4: SWEET × UMAMI         sweet-savory: teriyaki, ketchup, caramelized onion
INTERACTION  5: SOUR × SALTY          sour-salty: pickles, fermented foods, soy sauce with citrus
INTERACTION  6: SOUR × BITTER         sour-bitter: grapefruit, tonic, coffee with lemon
INTERACTION  7: SOUR × UMAMI          sour-umami: tomato, aged cheese, vinegar on meat
INTERACTION  8: SALTY × BITTER         salty-bitter: olives, some mineral waters, overcooked greens
INTERACTION  9: SALTY × UMAMI          salty-umami: soy sauce, parmesan, fish sauce, miso
INTERACTION 10: BITTER × UMAMI         bitter-umami: beer, dark soy, fermented paste

each interaction modulates perception:
    enhancement: one taste amplifies another (salty enhances umami)
    suppression: one taste masks another (sweet suppresses bitter)
    synergy: combined effect exceeds sum of parts (salt + umami in soy sauce)
    contrast: alternation highlights both (sweet after sour)


THE GUSTATORY SEA

TODO: full sea definition in tongue.xb

topology: surface map of the tongue
the tongue sea maps to the papillae distribution:
    fungiform papillae (anterior 2/3): all 5 taste types, moderate density
    circumvallate papillae (V-line posterior): all 5 types, high taste bud density
    foliate papillae (lateral posterior): sour-sensitive, moderate density
    palate and epiglottis: low density supplementary taste detection

device: gpu
capacity: approximately 5000-10000 (matching taste bud count)

the tongue sea couples to the brain sea through the gustatory cortex
cross-base coupling: base-5 × base-7 = 35 dimensions per coupled pair

for input: chemical sensors could map to qu-penttrit states
for output: the tongue as speech articulator connects to motor cortex (separate pathway)
